                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-229-person1325">
                  JEREMIAH 
                  AISH
               <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1325" type="surname" value="AISH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1325" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1325" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lived with Mr. Thomas Sell, of <placeName id="t18280221-229-crimeloc1221">Chiswell-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-229-crimeloc1221" type="placeName" value="Chiswell-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-229-crimeloc1221" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-229-off1219 t18280221-229-crimeloc1221"></join>, in October last, when the saddle was lost; the prisoner worked occasionally there; the saddle was in one of the stables - I cannot say when I saw it last; Asbury came to me with the duplicate - it was pawned in Fore-street; when I saw it, I was not quite sure that it was my master's; Asbury asked me to buy the ticket - the prisoner never worked in the yard.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-229-person1326">
                  JAMES 
                  ASBURY
               <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1326" type="surname" value="ASBURY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1326" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1326" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a sadler, and live at No. 7, White-street, Little Moor-fields. The prisoner called upon me with the duplicate of a saddle, on or about the 12th of January; he wished me to buy it - I thought he was an honest man - it was pawned for 9s. or 7s. - I would have nothing to do with it; he said the duplicate belonged to another man; I told him if it was worth buying, I knew a person who would buy it - I went to Jeremiah Aish, and we went to Fore-street and took it out, and looked at it; he asked me what the person wanted for it, I told him 9s., he said he would give 5s., and something for himself; the prisoner was taken up that day.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-229-person1327">
                  JOB 
                  VALENTINE WATKINS
               <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1327" type="surname" value="VALENTINE WATKINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1327" type="given" value="JOB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1327" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Jacob Russel, a pawnbroker, No. 43. Fore-street. The saddle was redeemed by Jeremiah Aish; it was pawned on the 25th of December, by the prisoner, in his own name; I asked if it was his brother Harry's; he said it was; I advanced 7s. upon it - it is worth about 14s.; it was an old one; it was looked at first - about two hours after Aish came and took it out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-229-person1328">
                  JOHN 
                  BROWN
               <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1328" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1328" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1328" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. The prisoner was given into my custody, with the saddle.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-229-person1329">
                  JEREMIAH 
                  AISH
               <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1329" type="surname" value="AISH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1329" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-229-person1329" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. I have no doubt at all but that the saddle is my master's; the prisoner worked in the yard when his brother sent him - his brother used to come into the yard.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. A man came and asked for Macdonald - he said he had a saddle to sell; I told him I did not think he wanted one - he asked me to buy it - I said I had not money enough, and he asked me if I would pawn it; I asked him where he got it - he said from a man at the White Bear public-house; I went to pawn it - I told him to put my name on the ticket - I bought the ticket, and told other people so.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 21.</p>
